{"actual_usd":0.123865,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":162,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"I wouldn't say he became God's Son there.\" *I rub a thumb against a faint smear of dried clay on my apron, thinking a moment before I go on.* \"From the Christian way I've been taught it, he was always the Son, and he didn't become divine at any point — he already was. The baptism is more like a revealing, not a change.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting through the cloud-breaks.* \"You can find folks who've argued otherwise, but plainest to me is this: Jesus wasn't a man who got promoted into Godness. He came in the flesh already bearing what he was. His baptism matters because the Father names him openly and the Spirit descends — not because that's the first moment he turns into something he wasn't.\"","rolling_24h_usd":39.67065500000003,"run_id":"cfe2d098-e909-4643-a414-f0eff1f6da8b"}
